{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528197"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:39:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:39:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14271"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14271","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14271"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.34,0.09,0.3,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6966"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102181"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6966"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14271"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84645"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1594"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"2047"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12728"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16348"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30275"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31988"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32509"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35636"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38403"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40668"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44310"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102181"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 53-year-old Aboriginal woman presents to the General Practice clinic for review of her recent routine blood tests. She has a medical history of congestive cardiac failure secondary to rheumatic heart disease, mitral valve replacement, type 2 diabetes mellitus and depression. Her regular medications include perindopril, bisoprolol, spironolactone, warfarin, metformin and semaglutide. She smokes five cigarettes per day and does not drink alcohol. She reports mild shortness of breath when walking up hills or stairs but denies chest pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. She has pitting oedema to the mid-shins which she reports has been stable for the past few months. Her recent blood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 130 g/L (115-160)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean cell volume 80 fL (80-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean cell haemoglobin 25.5 pg (27.5-33)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIron 12 \u00b5mol/L (9-30)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETransferrin 2.5 g/L (2.0-3.6)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETransferrin saturation 22% (15-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFerritin 65 \u00b5g/L (10-85)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence oral iron supplementation","Reassure and continue current management","Arrange iron infusion","Commence oral furosemide","Refer for repeat echocardiogram"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPatients with heart failure require higher ferritin targets than the general population. Iron deficiency is diagnosed in patients with heart failure if ferritin is less than 100 \u00b5g/L, or if the transferrin saturation is less than 20% and ferritin is between 100-299. The chronic inflammatory state can elevate ferritin levels, masking true iron deficiency, which is why transferrin saturation is also considered in the diagnosis of iron deficiency in heart failure. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step is to arrange \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous iron infusion\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the recommended treatment in this setting. This patient has a ferritin level of 65 \u00b5g/L, which is within the reference range for the general population but suboptimal for patients with heart failure. Iron deficiency in heart failure carries significant clinical consequences, even in the absence of anaemia. It contributes to reduced exercise tolerance, poorer quality of life, increased hospitalisation rates, and higher mortality, so correcting deficiency is an important consideration in any management plan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing oral iron supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E is not the best option for this patient. Heart failure patients often have reduced absorption of oral iron supplements due to gut oedema and increased hepcidin levels meaning oral iron is not effective in this context. Iron infusion is preferred as it bypasses these absorption issues and provides a more rapid and effective iron repletion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassuring and continuing current management\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as it fails to address the suboptimal iron status in this heart failure patient. Even though the ferritin level is within the general reference range, it is below the target for heart failure patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing oral furosemide\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated based on the information provided. While furosemide is useful in the management of symptoms of hypervolaemia, the patient\u0027s shortness of breath is mild and only occurs with exertion, and her oedema is reported as stable. Addressing the iron deficiency is the priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferring for a repeat echocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E may be necessary at some point for ongoing management of heart failure, but it is not the most urgent next step given the suboptimal iron status.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic inflammation in heart failure can lead to functional iron deficiency, necessitating higher ferritin targets.","Iron infusion is preferred over oral supplementation in heart failure patients due to reduced absorption from gut oedema.","Iron deficiency in heart failure, even without anaemia, is associated with reduced exercise capacity and poorer quality of life."],"references":["Rizzo C, Carbonara R, Ruggieri R, Passantino A, Scrutinio D. Iron Deficiency: A New Target for Patients With Heart Failure. Front Cardiovasc Med. 2021 Aug 10;8:709872. Available at:  https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8383833/","Masini G, Graham FJ, Pellicori P, Cleland JGF, Cuthbert JJ, Kazmi S, et al. Criteria for Iron Deficiency in Patients With Heart Failure. Journal of the American College of Cardiology. 2022 Feb;79(4):341\u201351. Available at: https://www.jacc.org/doi/10.1016/j.jacc.2021.11.039","Alnuwaysir RIS, Hoes MF, van Veldhuisen DJ, van der Meer P, Grote Beverborg N. Iron Deficiency in Heart Failure: Mechanisms and Pathophysiology. J Clin Med. 2021 Dec 27;11(1):125. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8745653/","Atherton, John J. et al. National Heart Foundation of Australia and Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand: Guidelines for the Prevention, Detection, and Management of Heart Failure in Australia 2018. Heart, Lung and Circulation, Volume 27, Issue 10, 1123 - 1208. Available at: https://www.heartlungcirc.org/article/S1443-9506(18)31777-3/fulltext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84645"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14271"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84645"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-10T08:58:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-10T09:00:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6966"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102181"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"u